{"title_page": "Comprimario", "text_new": "A '''comprimario''' is a small supporting role in an [[opera]]<ref>https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/NewDesign/fglossary.files/bglossary.files/Comprimario.htm</ref> (or a singer who sings those roles).<ref>http://patriciagray.net/Operahtmls/terms.html</ref> The word is derived from the [[Italian language|Italian]] \"''con primario''\", or \"with the primary\", meaning that the ''comprimario'' role (or singer) is not a principal role (or singer).<ref>http://enciclopedia_universal.esacademic.com/172152/comprimario</ref>  The term usually refers to characters who do not sing any full-length arias or long scenes (although mute characters who do not sing at all, are not considered ''comprimarios'').\n\nMany singers began their careers as ''comprimario'' singers; many others end their careers that way when they become too infirm to cope with long roles; some have made a career out of singing such parts.  Among these latter are singers such as [[Anthony Laciura]], [[Jean Kraft]], [[Nico Castel]] and [[Charles Anthony (tenor)|Charles Anthony]] of the [[Metropolitan Opera]]; others include [[Plinio Clabassi]] and Karl D\u00f6nch.\n\n==Some notable ''comprimario'' roles==\n\nNotable ''comprimario'' roles, in operas which are performed often, include Antonio and Barbarina in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', the Speaker of the Temple, the Two Men in Armor, and two of the priests in ''[[The Magic Flute]]'', the Police Sergeant and Ambrogio in ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'', Count Monterone's prison guard, Count Ceprano's wife, the page, and Giovanna the nursemaid, in ''[[Rigoletto]]'', the Messenger in ''[[Aida]]'', the Count Lerma and the Voice from Heaven in ''[[Don Carlos]]'', the Night Watchman in ''[[Die Meistersinger von N\u00fcrnberg]]'', the Shepherd in ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', the Steersman in ''[[The Flying Dutchman]]'', the physician and the apparitions in ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'', the Judge in ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'', the Forest Bird in ''[[Siegfried (opera)|Siegfried]]'', the four noblemen who conspire with Friedrich von Telramund in ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', the individual Grail-knights and the Esquires in ''[[Parsifal (opera)|Parsifal]]'', the First and Second Prisoners in ''[[Fidelio]]'', the Police Officer and the Notary in ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', the Police Officer (a different one) and Shchelkalov in ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]'', the Wig-Maker and the Lackey in ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'', the Wedding Registrar in ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', the Mandarin in ''[[Turandot]]'', Orest's servant in ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', and Frasquita and Mercedes in ''[[Carmen]]''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Opera terms}}\n\n[[Category:Italian opera terminology]]\n\n{{Opera-stub}}\n", "text_old": "A '''comprimario''' is a small supporting role in an [[opera]]<ref>https://www.naxos.com/mainsite/NewDesign/fglossary.files/bglossary.files/Comprimario.htm</ref> (or a singer who sings those roles)<ref>http://patriciagray.net/Operahtmls/terms.html</ref>. The word is derived from the [[Italian language|Italian]] \"''con primario''\", or \"with the primary\", meaning that the ''comprimario'' role (or singer) is not a principal role (or singer).<ref>http://enciclopedia_universal.esacademic.com/172152/comprimario</ref>  The term usually refers to characters who do not sing any full-length arias or long scenes (although mute characters who do not sing at all, are not considered ''comprimarios'').\n\nMany singers began their careers as ''comprimario'' singers; many others end their careers that way when they become too infirm to cope with long roles; some have made a career out of singing such parts.  Among these latter are singers such as [[Anthony Laciura]], [[Jean Kraft]], [[Nico Castel]] and [[Charles Anthony (tenor)|Charles Anthony]] of the [[Metropolitan Opera]]; others include [[Plinio Clabassi]] and Karl D\u00f6nch.\n\n==Some notable ''comprimario'' roles==\n\nNotable ''comprimario'' roles, in operas which are performed often, include Antonio and Barbarina in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', the Speaker of the Temple, the Two Men in Armor, and two of the priests in ''[[The Magic Flute]]'', the Police Sergeant and Ambrogio in ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'', Count Monterone's prison guard, Count Ceprano's wife, the page, and Giovanna the nursemaid, in ''[[Rigoletto]]'', the Messenger in ''[[Aida]]'', the Count Lerma and the Voice from Heaven in ''[[Don Carlos]]'', the Night Watchman in ''[[Die Meistersinger von N\u00fcrnberg]]'', the Shepherd in ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', the Steersman in ''[[The Flying Dutchman]]'', the physician and the apparitions in ''[[Macbeth (opera)|Macbeth]]'', the Judge in ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'', the Forest Bird in ''[[Siegfried (opera)|Siegfried]]'', the four noblemen who conspire with Friedrich von Telramund in ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', the individual Grail-knights and the Esquires in ''[[Parsifal (opera)|Parsifal]]'', the First and Second Prisoners in ''[[Fidelio]]'', the Police Officer and the Notary in ''[[Der Rosenkavalier]]'', the Police Officer (a different one) and Shchelkalov in ''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]'', the Wig-Maker and the Lackey in ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'', the Wedding Registrar in ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'', the Mandarin in ''[[Turandot]]'', Orest's servant in ''[[Elektra (opera)|Elektra]]'', and Frasquita and Mercedes in ''[[Carmen]]''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Opera terms}}\n\n[[Category:Italian opera terminology]]\n\n{{Opera-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comprimario"}
{"title_page": "Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard", "text_new": "[[File:Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard.jpg|thumb|Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard]]\nThe '''Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard''' ({{IPA-fr|k\u0254\u0303pl\u025bks sp\u0254\u0281tif klod \u0281obij\u0251\u0281|lang}}), abbreviated '''CSCR''', is a multi-purpose [[sport]] facility, located in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada, in the borough of [[Ahuntsic-Cartierville]].\n\n==History==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard was built for the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. It played host to the [[Handball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|handball]] and [[Water polo at the 1976 Summer Olympics|water polo]] competitions as well as being the training centre for [[Athletics at the 1976 Summer Olympics|athletics]], [[Swimming at the 1976 Summer Olympics|swimming]] and [[Field hockey at the 1976 Summer Olympics|field hockey]] during the games.\n\n==Overview==\nThe facility is made up of two buildings: the Michel-Normandin arena and the main building itself. At the heart of the facility lies a ten-lane [[Olympic-size swimming pool]] and smaller pool with diving towers, home to the award-winning [[CAMO]] swim club, as well as an indoor track, an omni-sport training room and a number of [[gym]]nasiums. On the grounds lie a number of other installations: a running track, a regulation-sized [[Association football|soccer]] pitch, a second pitch with an artificial surface, originally designed for [[field hockey]], but resurfaced in 2006 and configured for soccer and [[Canadian football]], [[tennis]] courts, [[baseball]] diamonds, and so forth. The running track and the large soccer pitch sit in the middle of a 6,500-seat stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.ville.montreal.qc.ca/banque311/content/complexe-sportif-claude-robillard-location|title=Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard : location {{!}} Banque d'information 311|website=www1.ville.montreal.qc.ca|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nThe facility plays host to many national and international sporting competitions. Yearly events include the ''Jeux de Montreal'' and the ''[[D\u00e9fi sportif]]'' (for handicapped athletes). The facility is also the headquarters for a number of clubs, some of which participate at an elite level, while others, such as Sports Montr\u00e9al and APADOR, provide services to the general public.\n\nMontreal's soccer team, the [[Montreal Impact]], also played its home games on the large soccer pitch from 1993 to 2007 and both the professional team and their academy trained there until 2015. Montreal Impact's USL-Pro affiliate [[FC Montreal]] play their games at Claude Robillard in 2016.<ref>http://www.impactmontreal.com/en/news/2014/09/montreal-usl-pro-team</ref>\n\n==Origin of the name==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard was named for [[Claude Robillard]], who was the first director of the City of Montreal's [[urban planning]] department.\n\n==High-performance training==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard is a centre for high-performance training for a number of sports, including:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Archery]]\n* [[Badminton]]\n* [[Baseball]]\n* [[Boxing]]\n* [[Canadian football]] \n* [[Diving (sport)|Diving]]\n* [[Fencing]]\n* [[Figure skating]]\n* [[Gymnastics]]\n* [[Team handball|Handball]]\n* [[Judo]]\n* [[Karate]]\n* [[Soccer]]\n* [[Softball]]\n* [[Speed skating]]\n* [[swimming (sport)|Swimming]]\n* [[Table tennis]]\n* [[Track and field]]\n* [[Ultimate Frisbee]]\n* [[Water polo]]\n* [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n* [[Wrestling]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1976/1976v2.pdf 1976 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 2. pp.&nbsp;118\u201323.\n*[http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=2236,2887379&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL City of Montreal] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.sportsmontreal.com/ Sports Montr\u00e9al] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.defisportif.com/ D\u00e9fi sportif] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-new|first}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Home of the<br>[[Montreal Impact]]|years=1993&ndash;2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Saputo Stadium]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{coord|45|33|14.83|N|73|38|11.87|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n{{Montreal Impact}}\n{{1976 Summer Olympic venues}}\n{{Olympic venues handball}}\n{{Olympic venues water polo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claude-Robillard, Complexe sportif}}\n[[Category:Venues of the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Olympic handball venues]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Soccer venues in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Montreal Impact]]\n[[Category:Ahuntsic-Cartierville]]\n[[Category:1970s establishments in Quebec]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard.jpg|thumb|Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard]]\nThe '''Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard''' ({{IPA-fr|k\u0254\u0303pl\u025bks sp\u0254\u0281tif klod \u0281obij\u0251\u0281|lang}}), abbreviated '''CSCR''', is a multi-purpose [[sport]] facility, located in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada, in the borough of [[Ahuntsic-Cartierville]].\n\n==History==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard was built for the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. It played host to the [[Handball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|handball]] and [[Water polo at the 1976 Summer Olympics|water polo]] competitions as well as being the training centre for [[Athletics at the 1976 Summer Olympics|athletics]], [[Swimming at the 1976 Summer Olympics|swimming]] and [[Field hockey at the 1976 Summer Olympics|field hockey]] during the games.\n\n==Overview==\nThe facility is made up of two buildings: the Michel-Normandin arena and the main building itself. At the heart of the facility lies a ten-lane [[Olympic-size swimming pool]] and smaller pool with diving towers, home to the award-winning [[CAMO]] swim club, as well as an indoor track, an omni-sport training room and a number of [[gym]]nasiums. On the grounds lie a number of other installations: a running track, a regulation-sized [[Association football|soccer]] pitch, a second pitch with an artificial surface, originally designed for [[field hockey]], but resurfaced in 2006 and configured for soccer and [[Canadian football]], [[tennis]] courts, [[baseball]] diamonds, and so forth. The running track and the large soccer pitch sit in the middle of a 6,500-seat stadium<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www1.ville.montreal.qc.ca/banque311/content/complexe-sportif-claude-robillard-location|title=Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard : location {{!}} Banque d'information 311|website=www1.ville.montreal.qc.ca|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>.\n\nThe facility plays host to many national and international sporting competitions. Yearly events include the ''Jeux de Montreal'' and the ''[[D\u00e9fi sportif]]'' (for handicapped athletes). The facility is also the headquarters for a number of clubs, some of which participate at an elite level, while others, such as Sports Montr\u00e9al and APADOR, provide services to the general public.\n\nMontreal's soccer team, the [[Montreal Impact]], also played its home games on the large soccer pitch from 1993 to 2007 and both the professional team and their academy trained there until 2015. Montreal Impact's USL-Pro affiliate [[FC Montreal]] play their games at Claude Robillard in 2016.<ref>http://www.impactmontreal.com/en/news/2014/09/montreal-usl-pro-team</ref>\n\n==Origin of the name==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard was named for [[Claude Robillard]], who was the first director of the City of Montreal's [[urban planning]] department.\n\n==High-performance training==\nThe Complexe sportif Claude-Robillard is a centre for high-performance training for a number of sports, including:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Archery]]\n* [[Badminton]]\n* [[Baseball]]\n* [[Boxing]]\n* [[Canadian football]] \n* [[Diving (sport)|Diving]]\n* [[Fencing]]\n* [[Figure skating]]\n* [[Gymnastics]]\n* [[Team handball|Handball]]\n* [[Judo]]\n* [[Karate]]\n* [[Soccer]]\n* [[Softball]]\n* [[Speed skating]]\n* [[swimming (sport)|Swimming]]\n* [[Table tennis]]\n* [[Track and field]]\n* [[Ultimate Frisbee]]\n* [[Water polo]]\n* [[Olympic weightlifting|Weightlifting]]\n* [[Wrestling]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://library.la84.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1976/1976v2.pdf 1976 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 2. pp.&nbsp;118\u201323.\n*[http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=2236,2887379&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL City of Montreal] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.sportsmontreal.com/ Sports Montr\u00e9al] {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.defisportif.com/ D\u00e9fi sportif] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-new|first}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Home of the<br>[[Montreal Impact]]|years=1993&ndash;2007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Saputo Stadium]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{coord|45|33|14.83|N|73|38|11.87|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=title}}\n\n{{Montreal Impact}}\n{{1976 Summer Olympic venues}}\n{{Olympic venues handball}}\n{{Olympic venues water polo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Claude-Robillard, Complexe sportif}}\n[[Category:Venues of the 1976 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletics (track and field) venues in Quebec]]\n[[Category:Olympic handball venues]]\n[[Category:Olympic water polo venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Soccer venues in Montreal]]\n[[Category:Montreal Impact]]\n[[Category:Ahuntsic-Cartierville]]\n[[Category:1970s establishments in Quebec]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complexe_sportif_Claude-Robillard"}
{"title_page": "Comparison of the Chernobyl and Fukushima nuclear accidents", "text_new": "__NOTOC__\nThe following table compares the [[nuclear accident]]s at the [[Chernobyl disaster|Chernobyl]] (1986) and [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima Daiichi]] (2011) [[nuclear power plant]]s, the only [[International Nuclear Event Scale|INES]] level 7 nuclear accidents to date.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Plant Name\n! [[Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant|Chernobyl]]\n{{Css Image Crop\n |Image = Chernobyl_Nuclear_Power_Plant.jpg\n |bSize = 200\n |cWidth = 200\n |cHeight = 133\n |oLeft = 0\n |oTop = 0\n |Location = center\n |Description =\n }}\n! [[Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant|Fukushima Daiichi]]\n{{Css Image Crop\n |Image = Fukushima_I_by_Digital_Globe_crop.jpg\n |bSize = 200\n |cWidth = 200\n |cHeight = 133\n |oLeft = 0\n |oTop = 21\n |Location = center\n |Description =\n }}\n|-\n| '''Location''' || [[Soviet Union]] ([[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic]]) {{coord|51.38946|30.09914|display=inline}} || [[Japan]] {{coord|37.6665|141.0208|display=inline}}\n|-\n| '''Date of the accident''' || April 26, 1986 || March 11, 2011\n|-\n| '''[[International Nuclear Event Scale|INES]] Level''' || 7 || 7\n|-\n| '''Plant commissioning date''' || 1977 || 1971\n|-\n| '''Years of operation before the accident''' || 9 years (plant)<br/>{{bulleted list|2 years (Unit 4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaea.org/PRIS/CountryStatistics/ReactorDetails.aspx?current=576|title=PRIS - Reactor Details|website=www.iaea.org|access-date=2016-07-14}}</ref>}} || 40 years (plant)<br/>{{bulleted list|40 years (Unit 1)|37 years (Unit 2)|35 years (Unit 3)|33 years (Unit 4)}}\n|-\n| '''Electrical output''' || plant (net): 3700 [[megawatt|MWe]] (4 reactors)<br/>reactors (net): 925 MWe (Units 1&ndash;4) || plant (net): 4546 [[megawatt|MWe]] (6 reactors)<br/>reactors (net): 439 MWe (Unit 1), 760 MWe (Units 2&ndash;5), 1067 MWe (Unit 6)\n|-\n| '''Type of reactor''' || [[RBMK]]-1000 [[graphite moderated reactor|graphite moderated]], 2nd generation reactor without containment || [[Boiling water reactor|BWR-3]] and [[Boiling water reactor|BWR-4]] reactors with [[Containment building#Boiling water reactors|Mark I]] containment vessels\n|-\n| '''Number of reactors''' || 4 on site; 1 involved in accident || 6 on site; 4 (and [[spent fuel pool]]s) involved in accident; one of the four reactors was empty of fuel at the time of the accident.\n|-\n| '''Amount of nuclear fuel in affected reactors''' ||  1 reactor - 210 tons (spent fuel pools not involved in incident)<ref name=\"nei-chernobyl-summary-fs\">{{cite web|title=Chernobyl Accident And Its Consequences - Nuclear Energy Institute|url=https://www.nei.org/Master-Document-Folder/Backgrounders/Fact-Sheets/Chernobyl-Accident-And-Its-Consequences|website=www.nei.org|publisher=Nuclear Energy Institute|accessdate=9 April 2017}} - note that figures were converted into US tons</ref> || 4 reactors - 854 tons (81 tons in Unit 1 reactor, 111 tons in Unit 2 reactor, 111 tons in Unit 3 reactor, 0 tons in Unit 4 reactor (defueled), 59 tons in Unit 1 spent fuel pool (SFP), 119 tons in Unit 2 SFP, 104 tons in Unit 3 SFP, and 269 tons in Unit 4 SFP){{efn|183.3 kg/assembly;<ref name=\"background-fuel-basic\">{{cite techreport| title=Fukushima: Background on Reactors| url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/Safety-and-Security/Safety-of-Plants/Appendices/Fukushima--Reactor-Background/| date=February 2012| accessdate=4 September 2014}} - 183.3 kg / assembly</ref> 400 assemblies in reactor 1, 548 assemblies in reactors 2&3, 0 assemblies in reactor 4, total of 1496 assemblies in reactors 1-4;<ref name=\"background-fuel-basic\" /><ref>{{cite web|author1=International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)|authorlink1=International Atomic Energy Agency|title=The Fukushima Daiichi Accident: Technical Volume 2/5 - Safety Assessment|url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/Publications/PDF/AdditionalVolumes/P1710/Pub1710-TV2-Web.pdf|publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)|accessdate=1 May 2017|page=74|date=August 2015}}</ref> 292 assemblies in Unit 1 spent fuel pool (SFP), 587 assemblies in Unit 2 SFP, 514 assemblies in Unit 3 SFP, 1331 assemblies in Unit 4 SFP, total of 2724 assemblies in spent fuel pools 1-4.<ref>{{cite web|author1=International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)|authorlink1=International Atomic Energy Agency|title=The Fukushima Daiichi Accident: Technical Volume 1/5 - Description and Context of the Accident|url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/Publications/PDF/AdditionalVolumes/P1710/Pub1710-TV1-Web.pdf|publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)|accessdate=1 May 2017|page=66|date=August 2015}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| '''Cause of the accident''' || Proximate cause was human error and violation of procedures. The unsafe reactor design caused instability at low power due to a positive [[void coefficient]] and steam formation. When an improper test was conducted at 1:00 am at low power, the reactor became [[prompt critical]]. This was followed by a [[steam explosion]] that exposed the fuel, a raging fire, and a [[core meltdown]]. The fire lasted for days to weeks, and there is controversy over whether it was the fuel burning, nuclear decay heating or whether the [[graphite]] moderator that made up most of the core was involved.  See [[Chernobyl Disaster]], Note 1, for more discussion. || The plants were not designed with consideration of such a large [[tsunami]]. Subsequent review did not lead to mitigation. A major [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|earthquake and tsunami]] caused the destruction of power lines and backup generators. Once the plants were without external power and the generators were flooded, a catastrophic [[decay heat]] casualty ensued, leading to major reactor plant damage including [[nuclear meltdown|meltdown]]s and explosive loss of [[reactor containment]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n|-\n| '''Maximum level of [[radiation]] detected''' || 300 [[sievert|Sv]]/h shortly after the explosion in vicinity of the reactor core.<ref name=\"medv\">{{cite web|url = http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA335076|archive-url = https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20110324215518/http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA335076|url-status = dead|archive-date = 2011-03-24|title = JPRS Report: Soviet Union Economic Affairs Chernobyl Notebook|author = B. Medvedev|date = June 1989|publisher = Novy Mir|accessdate = 27 March 2011|edition = Republished by the Foreign Broadcast Information Service}}</ref> || 530 [[sievert|Sv]]/h inside Unit 2 containment vessel in 2017 according to Japan Times.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/02/03/national/fukushima-radiation-level-highest-since-march-11/#.XRiy_I-xWUk|title = Fukushima radiation level highest since March 11|newspaper = The Japan Times Online|date = 2017-02-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Radioactivity released''' || According to IAEA, total release was {{convert|14|EBq|PBq|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaea.org/sites/default/files/chernobyl.pdf|title=Chernobyl's Legacy: Health, Environmental and Socio-Economic Impacts and Recommendations to the Governments of Belarus, the Russian Federation and Ukraine. The Chernobyl Forum: 2003\u20132005 Second revised version|work=[[IAEA]]|date=April 1, 2006|accessdate=Apr 25, 2019}}</ref> {{convert|5.2|EBq|PBq|abbr=on}} in iodine-131 equivalent <ref>{{cite journal|title=Three Mile Island, Chernobyl, and Fukushima, A comparison of three nuclear reactor calamities reveals some key differences|work=[[IEEE]]|date=Nov 1, 2011|doi=10.1109/MSPEC.2011.6056644}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/Safety-and-Security/Safety-of-Plants/Chernobyl-Accident/#.UncVJRD_EQ0|title=Chernobyl Accident 1986|work=[[World Nuclear Association]]|date=Jun 1, 2013|accessdate=Apr 25, 2019}}</ref> || As of 2014, a peer reviewed estimate of the total was 340&ndash;780 P[[Becquerel|Bq]], with 80% falling into the Pacific Ocean.<ref>{{cite journal |url=  |title=Comparison of the Chernobyl and Fukushima nuclear accidents: A review of the environmental impacts | doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2013.10.029 |pmid=24189103 | volume=470-471 |journal=Science of the Total Environment |pages=800\u2013817|year=2014 |last1=Steinhauser |first1=Georg |last2=Brandl |first2=Alexander |last3=Johnson |first3=Thomas E. |bibcode=2014ScTEn.470..800S }}</ref> Radiation continues to be released into the Pacific via groundwater.\n|-\n| '''Area affected''' || An area up to {{convert|500|km|mi}} away contaminated, according to the United Nations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unscear.org/docs/reports/2000/Volume%20II_Effects/AnnexJ_pages%20451-566.pdf|title=ANNEX J. Exposures and effects of the Chernobyl accident.|last=|first=|date=2000|website=|publisher=[[United Nations]] UNSCEAR|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unscear.org/docs/JfigXI.pdf|title=Figure XI. Surface ground deposition of caesium-137 released in Europe after the Chernobyl accident [D13].|last=|first=|date=2000|website=|publisher=[[United Nation]] UNSCEAR Report|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unscear.org/docs/JfigVI.pdf|title=Figure VI. Surface ground deposition of caesium-137 released in the Chernobyl accident [I1, L3].|last=|first=|date=2000|website=|publisher=[[United Nation]] UNSCEAR Report|access-date=}}</ref> || Radiation levels exceeding annual limits seen over {{convert|60|km|mi}} to northwest and {{convert|40|km|mi}} to south-southwest, according to officials.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n|-\n| '''[[Exclusion Zone]] Area''' || 30&nbsp;km || 20&nbsp;km (30&nbsp;km voluntary) extending north-west to 45&nbsp;km in the downwind direction to [[Iitate, Fukushima]]<ref name=wna-201602>{{cite web |url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/information-library/safety-and-security/safety-of-plants/appendices/fukushima-radiation-exposure.aspx |title=Fukushima: Radiation Exposure |publisher=World Nuclear Association |date=February 2016 |accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Population relocated''' || 335,000 (About 115,000 from areas surrounding the reactor in 1986; about 220,000 people from [[Belarus]], the [[Russian Federation]] and [[Ukraine]] after 1986) || 154,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reconstruction.go.jp/english/topics/GEJE/index.html|title=Reconstruction Agency|website=www.reconstruction.go.jp|access-date=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Population returned''' || None || 122,000<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/fukushima-residents-return-despite-radiation/|title=Fukushima Residents Return Despite Radiation|website=www.scientificamerican.com|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Direct fatalities from the accident''' || Two immediate trauma deaths; 28 deaths from [[Acute Radiation Syndrome]] out of 134 showing symptoms; four from an industrial accident (helicopter crash); 15 deaths from radiation-genic thyroid cancers (as of 2005);<ref>{{cite techreport| url=http://www.unscear.org/docs/reports/2008/11-80076_Report_2008_Annex_D.pdf| title=Health effects due to radiation from the Chernobyl accident (Annex D of the 2008 UNSCEAR Report)| date=2011| publisher=UNSCEAR}}</ref> as many as 4000 to 90000 cancer related deaths.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2005/pr38/en/ |title = WHO &#124; Chernobyl: The true scale of the accident}}</ref> || None\n|-\n| '''Current status''' || All reactors were shut down by 2000. The damaged reactor was covered by a hastily built steel and concrete structure called the ''[[Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant sarcophagus|sarcophagus]]''. A [[New Safe Confinement]] structure was installed in November 2016, from which the plant will be cleaned up and decommissioned. || [[Cold shutdown]] declared on 16 December 2011, but decommissioning is likely to take 30 to 40 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/07/toshiba-idUSL3E7F73E720110407 |title=UPDATE 1-Toshiba proposes to scrap Fukushima nuclear plant-Nikkei |accessdate=27 July 2013 |work=Reuters |first=Kavyanjali |last=Kaushik |date=7 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-20140310\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/10/fukushima-operator-dump-contaminated-water-pacific |title=Fukushima operator may have to dump contaminated water into Pacific |author=Justin Mccurry |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> All fuel rods in reactor 4 pool removed. [[Fukushima disaster cleanup]] is ongoing.\n|}\n\n==Radioactive contamination discharge==\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\"   \n|-   \n!rowspan=2| Report date\n!rowspan=2| Place   \n!rowspan=2| Period\n!colspan=2| [[Iodine-131]]<br />(TBq)   \n!colspan=2| [[Caesium-137]]<br />(TBq)   \n!rowspan=2| Source   \n|-   \n!from   \n!to   \n!from   \n!to   \n|-   \n|2002   \n|Chernobyl   \n|25 April \u2013 June 1986   \n|align=right| 1,600,000\n|align=right| 1,940,000\n|align=right| 59,000\n|align=right| 111,000\n|[[Nuclear Energy Agency|NEA]]<ref name=\"nea-tschernobyl\">{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318233129/http://www.oecd-nea.org/rp/chernobyl/c02.html |date=2012-03-18 }}2002, archived from [http://www.oecd-nea.org/rp/chernobyl/c02.html Original] on 20 April 2011, retrieved on 6 April 2011.</ref>\n|-   \n|22 March 2011   \n|Fukushima   \n|12 \u2013 15 March 2011   \n|colspan=2 align=center| 400,000\n|align=right| 3,000\n|align=right| 30,000\n|ZAMG<ref name=\"zamg-2011-03-22\">{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914210019/http://www.zamg.ac.at/aktuell/index.php?seite=3&artikel=ZAMG_2011-03-22GMT13:31 |date=14 September 2011 }}{{in lang|de}}. ZAMG, 22 March 2011, archived from [http://www.zamg.ac.at/aktuell/index.php?seite=3&artikel=ZAMG_2011-03-22GMT13:31 Original] on 20 April 2011, retrieved on 20 April 2011.</ref>\n|-   \n|2 April 2011   \n|Fukushima   \n|12 \u2013 19 March 2011   \n|align=right| 10,000\n|align=right| 700,001\n|align=right| 1,000\n|align=rig