{"title_page": "Sonnet 48", "text_new": "{{Sonnet|48|Sonnet 48 1609.jpg|The first five lines of Sonnet 48 in the 1609 Quarto|\nHow careful was I, when I took my way,\nEach trifle under truest bars to thrust,\nThat to my use it might unused stay\nFrom hands of falsehood, in sure wards of trust!\nBut thou, to whom my jewels trifles are,\nMost worthy comfort, now my greatest grief,\nThou, best of dearest and mine only care,\nArt left the prey of every vulgar thief.\nThee have I not lock\u2019d up in any chest,\nSave where thou art not, though I feel thou art,\nWithin the gentle closure of my breast,\nFrom whence at pleasure thou mayst come and part;\n:And even thence thou wilt be stol\u2019n, I fear,\n:For truth proves thievish for a prize so dear.\n|source=<ref>{{cite book |title=The Works of Shakespeare: Sonnets |editor-first=C[harles] Knox |editor-last=Pooler |series=The Arden Shakespeare [1st series] |location=London |publisher=Methuen & Company |date=1918 |url=https://archive.org/details/sonnetseditedbyc00shakuoft |oclc=4770201}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Sonnet 48''' is one of [[The Sonnets|154 sonnets]] written by the English playwright and poet [[William Shakespeare]]. It is a member of the [[The Sonnets#Fair Youth|Fair Youth]] sequence, in which the poet expresses his love towards a young man.\n\n==Structure==\nSonnet 48 is an English or Shakespearean [[sonnet]], a type of sonnet that contains three [[quatrain]]s followed by a final rhyming [[couplet]]. It follows the form's typical [[rhyme scheme]], ABAB CDCD EFEF GG, and is written in [[iambic pentameter]] based on five pairs of metrically weak/strong syllabic positions per line. The second line exemplifies a regular iambic pentameter:\n\n<pre style=\"border:none;background-color:transparent;margin-left:1em\">\n\u00d7      / \u00d7  /  \u00d7    /\u00d7    /    \u00d7    / \nEach trifle under truest bars to thrust, (48.2)\n</pre>\n:/ = ''ictus'', a metrically strong syllabic position. \u00d7 = ''nonictus''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Shakespeare sonnets bibliography}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shakespeares-sonnets.com/xlviiicomm.htm Analysis]\n\n{{Shakespeare}}\n{{Shakespeare's sonnets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonnet 048}}\n[[Category:British poems]]\n[[Category:Sonnets by William Shakespeare]]\n", "text_old": "{{Sonnet|48|Sonnet 48 1609.jpg|The first five lines of Sonnet 48 in the 1609 Quarto|\nHow careful was I, when I took my way,\nEach trifle under truest bars to thrust,\nThat to my use it might unused stay\nFrom hands of falsehood, in sure wards of rust!\nBut thou, to whom my jewels trifles are,\nMost worthy comfort, now my greatest grief,\nThou, best of dearest and mine only care,\nArt left the prey of every vulgar thief.\nThee have I not lock\u2019d up in any chest,\nSave where thou art not, though I feel thou art,\nWithin the gentle closure of my breast,\nFrom whence at pleasure thou mayst come and part;\n:And even thence thou wilt be stol\u2019n, I fear,\n:For truth proves thievish for a prize so dear.\n|source=<ref>{{cite book |title=The Works of Shakespeare: Sonnets |editor-first=C[harles] Knox |editor-last=Pooler |series=The Arden Shakespeare [1st series] |location=London |publisher=Methuen & Company |date=1918 |url=https://archive.org/details/sonnetseditedbyc00shakuoft |oclc=4770201}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Sonnet 48''' is one of [[The Sonnets|154 sonnets]] written by the English playwright and poet [[William Shakespeare]]. It is a member of the [[The Sonnets#Fair Youth|Fair Youth]] sequence, in which the poet expresses his love towards a young man.\n\n==Structure==\nSonnet 48 is an English or Shakespearean [[sonnet]], a type of sonnet that contains three [[quatrain]]s followed by a final rhyming [[couplet]]. It follows the form's typical [[rhyme scheme]], ABAB CDCD EFEF GG, and is written in [[iambic pentameter]] based on five pairs of metrically weak/strong syllabic positions per line. The second line exemplifies a regular iambic pentameter:\n\n<pre style=\"border:none;background-color:transparent;margin-left:1em\">\n\u00d7      / \u00d7  /  \u00d7    /\u00d7    /    \u00d7    / \nEach trifle under truest bars to thrust, (48.2)\n</pre>\n:/ = ''ictus'', a metrically strong syllabic position. \u00d7 = ''nonictus''.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Shakespeare sonnets bibliography}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shakespeares-sonnets.com/xlviiicomm.htm Analysis]\n\n{{Shakespeare}}\n{{Shakespeare's sonnets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonnet 048}}\n[[Category:British poems]]\n[[Category:Sonnets by William Shakespeare]]\n", "name_user": "James54742423", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonnet_48"}
